Part 1 - Getting started

A brief introduction installing zipline assuming you already have installed Conda on your computer (Mac in our case). I have tried different ways, through Pip or through an IDE. But conda was the most convenient. If you have updated to Catalina, you will have a 'zsh' shell rather than a 'bash' shell.

A separate text file opens to with some code, take the bottom part and copy and paste it.

Which activates bash. In order to use Zipline, it is best to create your own virtual environment. If you already have conda installed use the following command: **conda create --prefix file/path/of/backtest/name_of_your_env python=3.5**. This creates a virtual environment with python 3.5 installed and install the packages that are suggested.

Next, activate your virtual environment by: **conda activate /path/of/your/file/name_of_your_env**. You will see instead of (base) in front your use profile, the name and file path of your virtual environment:

Install **Zipline** through the command: **conda install -c Quantopian zipline**, and install the other suggested libraries.

Looking at the list of available files in the 'BACKTESTING' directory where we stored our virtual environment called 'my_env'

Part 2 : Getting jupyter notebook to make things easier (also for developing)

Even if you already have Jupyter Notebook installed, in order to use Zipline in your notebooks, you need to use your virtual environment as your kernel. Open your environment through conda activate. Then use: conda install nb_conda, and then enter jupyter notebook in your command line. Doing so, it will open your browser with a main menu. Then when you want to use Zipline you need to make sure you select the right kernel, that your virtual environment, as seen in the last picture
